    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Human Touch</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Atkinson letter about Mar 25 article on computerized music for Broadway musicals says human element is needed (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Theater's Alive With the Sound of Laptops'' by Jesse Green [March 25]:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Theater's Alive With the Sound of Laptops'' by Jesse Green [March 25]:</p>
        <p>Live performers bring style, nuance and musical expression that come from years of research and programming the best computer we have access to: the human brain. At their core Broadway musicals transmit human messages to human audiences. To dismiss live musicians or any other human element involved in the creation of musicals removes a defining characteristic of this art form.</p>
        <p>Michael Atkinson  Manhattan</p>
        <p>The writer is a member of the orchestra for ''Les Mis√©rables.''</p>
        <p>LAPTOPS ON BROADWAY</p>
      </block>
